<hl>
<seg id=1> Information Minister Rahmat: "Reformasi" Demonstrators Should Not Become Foreign Puppets </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Kuala Lumpur) Mohamad Rahmat, information minister for Malaysia, said that people joining the "Reformasi" movement should not become puppets of foreign powers and destroy the country. They should instead should adopt a more sensible method of expressing their opinions, he said. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said resorting to violence or causing unrest are not as effective as using sensible methods to express what one is feeling. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Malaysian news agency Bernama reported that Mohamad Rahmat, after attending an information bureau Family Day activity, spoke to the media and said that the government has already adopted measures to allow citizens to fully express what they are thinking through the 500 "Voice Your Opinion Centers" set up all over the country. He called these centers an appropriate channel for allowing people to express their ideas and opinions about the country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He said the government is going to study the people's opinions in order to improve itself and meet the broad needs of the country's citizens. </seg>
<seg id=6> He stressed that this is the method of a democratic country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He also urged demonstrators to consider carefully what would result from the demonstration movement, saying that in the 41 years of Malaysia's independence the whole citizenry have worked hard to contribute to the development of the country, and that only because of them do they have the prosperity they do today. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> He said the demonstrators have received support from outside the country, and that this is going one step further in opposing the government, but that they don't realize that this is a serious act of selling out the country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> He said, "We welcome foreigners who want to come to Malaysia to invest, but if they give money to demonstrators we will definitely protest against that." </seg>
</p>
